## Root Cause

The `MudSelect` component was not triggering validation when focus left the control. The issue was in the `OnFocusOutAsync` method in `MudSelect.razor.cs`.

When the user tabbed out of an empty/required `MudSelect`:
1. The inner `MudInput` element has `ReadOnly="true"`, so its `OnBlurredAsync` returns early without triggering validation
2. The outer div's `@onfocusout` handler (`OnFocusOutAsync`) only handled the case where the dropdown menu was open (re-focusing the input for keyboard navigation), but did nothing when the menu was closed

In contrast, `MudTextField` passes its own `OnBlurredAsync` to the inner `MudInput` as the `OnBlur` callback, which properly triggers validation through the full chain.

## Fix

Modified `OnFocusOutAsync` in `MudSelect.razor.cs` to also trigger validation when the menu is **not** open:

```csharp
private async Task OnFocusOutAsync()
{
    if (_openState.Value)
    {
        await FocusAsync();  // Keep keyboard nav working in multi-select
    }
    else
    {
        Touched = true;       // Mark as touched
        await BeginValidateAsync();  // Trigger validation (e.g., Required)
    }
}
```

This ensures that when the user tabs away from an empty required `MudSelect`, the validation error is displayed just like it is for `MudTextField`.
